Netflix and Amazon Movies and TV Shows¶

1. Data Presentation¶

Each dataset contains 12 variables:

  • show_id : corresponds to the unique ID of the movie or show
  • type: indicates whether it is a movie or a TV show
  • title: the title of the movie/show
  • director : the production manager
  • cast: the actors in the movie/show
  • country: country in which the movie/show was produced
  • date_added: date the movie/show was added on Netflix
  • release_year: the actual release year of the movie/show
  • rating: content rating (TV-MA, TV-14, TV-PG, R, PG-13, NR, TV-Y7, TV-G, TV-Y, TV-Y7-FV, G, UR, NC-17). To see the meaning of the different content ratings: https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/TV_Parental_Guidelines
  • duration: for movies - length of the movie in minutes. For shows - number of seasons
  • listed_in: the genre of the movie/show, the category.
  • description : the description of the movie/show

2. Getting data¶

Data source: http://kaggle.com

  • Netflix file: netflix_titles.csv
  • Amazon file: amazon_prime_titles.csv

2.1 Import libraries¶

  • Counter is useful for counting the occurrences of elements in a list, tuple, or other iterable. This can be helpful in various data analysis and processing tasks, such as calculating frequencies, identifying popular items, or analyzing the distribution of elements in a dataset.

6. Statistics¶

6.1 Data preparation for Chi-Square Test¶

  • Create a contingency table that represents the counts of movies and TV shows in each dataset (Amazon and Netflix).
  • This will create a contingency table with rows representing movies and TV shows, and columns representing Amazon and Netflix. The values in the table will represent the counts of movies and TV shows in each dataset.
In [111]:
# Create a new column 'Media Type' in each DataFrame to distinguish between movies and TV shows.
netflix_df['Media Type'] = netflix_df['type'].map({'Movie': 'Movie', 'TV Show': 'TV Show'})
amazon_df['Media Type'] = amazon_df['type'].map({'Movie': 'Movie', 'TV Show': 'TV Show'})

# Create the contingency table
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(netflix_df['Media Type'], amazon_df['Media Type'])

# Display the contingency table
print(contingency_table)

Media Type  Movie  TV Show
Media Type                
Movie        4205      980
TV Show       112       35

6.2 Perform the chi-square test for independence using the contingency table.¶

In [112]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Perform the chi-square test for independence
chi2_stat, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

# Print the results
print("Chi-Square Statistic:", chi2_stat)
print("P-value:", p_value)
print("Degrees of Freedom:", dof)
print("Expected Frequencies Table:")
print(pd.DataFrame(expected, index=contingency_table.index, columns=contingency_table.columns))

Chi-Square Statistic: 1.9277937879791984
P-value: 0.16500001780333334
Degrees of Freedom: 1
Expected Frequencies Table:
Media Type        Movie     TV Show
Media Type                         
Movie       4197.982933  987.017067
TV Show      119.017067   27.982933

6.4 Calculate Cramer's V to quantify the strength of the association¶

In [113]:
# Given chi-square statistic and degrees of freedom
chi_square_statistic = 0.0
degrees_of_freedom = 0

# Sample size
sample_size = 5332  # Total number of observations (see contingecy table above)

# Number of rows and columns in the contingency table
num_rows = 2  # Movies and TV Shows
num_cols = 2  # Amazon and Netflix

# Calculate Cramer's V
cramers_v = np.sqrt(chi_square_statistic / (sample_size * min(num_rows - 1, num_cols - 1)))

print("Cramer's V:", cramers_v)

Cramer's V: 0.0

7. Merging Netflix and Amazon Prime¶

  • The on="show_id" parameter specifies the column to merge on, assuming there is a common column named "show_id" in both datasets. The how="inner" parameter performs an inner join, keeping only the rows that have matching show IDs in both datasets.
  • By specifying suffixes=("_netflix", "_prime"), the resulting merged dataset will have column names with the specified suffixes indicating the source of each column.
In [116]:
# Merge the datasets based on common columns (e.g., show_id) with custom suffixes
merged_df = pd.merge(netflix_df, amazon_df, on="show_id", how="inner", suffixes=("_netflix", "_amazon"))

# Set 'show_id' as index
merged_df = merged_df.set_index(['show_id'])

8.1 ANOVA¶

  • Duration and genre
In [131]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

# Create separate DataFrames for movies in Netflix and Amazon Prime
movies_netflix = merged_df[merged_df["type_netflix"] == "Movie"].copy()
movies_amazon = merged_df[merged_df["type_amazon"] == "Movie"].copy()

# Replace NaN values in the duration column with a default value (e.g., 0)
movies_netflix["duration_netflix"] = movies_netflix["duration_netflix"].str.replace(" min", "").replace(np.nan, 0).astype(int)
movies_amazon["duration_amazon"] = movies_amazon["duration_amazon"].str.replace(" min", "").replace(np.nan, 0).astype(int)

# Perform one-way ANOVA for Netflix
f_statistic_netflix, p_value_netflix = f_oneway(*[group["duration_netflix"] for name, group in movies_netflix.groupby("listed_in_netflix")])

# Perform one-way ANOVA for Amazon Prime
f_statistic_amazon, p_value_amazon = f_oneway(*[group["duration_amazon"] for name, group in movies_amazon.groupby("listed_in_amazon")])

# Print the results for Netflix
print("Netflix ANOVA Results:")
print("F-Statistic:", f_statistic_netflix)
print("p-value:", p_value_netflix)

# Print the results for Amazon Prime
print("Amazon Prime ANOVA Results:")
print("F-Statistic:", f_statistic_amazon)
print("p-value:", p_value_amazon)

Netflix ANOVA Results:
F-Statistic: 13.261493254812303
p-value: 0.0
Amazon Prime ANOVA Results:
F-Statistic: 4.118469900119845
p-value: 9.763516867944503e-108

The low p-values suggest that the differences observed in the attributes being compared, duration and genre, are unlikely to have occurred by random chance

8.2 CHI 2 TEST¶

  • Relationship between genre and content rating for both Netflix and Amazon Prime
In [134]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

# Filter for movies only in both datasets
netflix_movies = merged_df[merged_df["type_netflix"] == "Movie"]
amazon_movies = merged_df[merged_df["type_amazon"] == "Movie"]

# Create a contingency table of genre (listed_in) and content rating (rating) for Netflix movies
netflix_contingency_table = pd.crosstab(merged_df["listed_in_netflix"], merged_df["rating_netflix"])

# Create a contingency table of genre (listed_in) and content rating (rating) for Amazon Prime movies
amazon_contingency_table = pd.crosstab(merged_df["listed_in_amazon"], merged_df["rating_amazon"])

# Perform chi-square test for Netflix movies
netflix_chi2_statistic, netflix_p_value, netflix_dof, netflix_expected = chi2_contingency(netflix_contingency_table)

# Perform chi-square test for Amazon Prime movies
amazon_chi2_statistic, amazon_p_value, amazon_dof, amazon_expected = chi2_contingency(amazon_contingency_table)

# Print the results for Netflix dataset
print("Netflix Chi-square Test Results:")
print("Chi-square Statistic:", netflix_chi2_statistic)
print("p-value:", netflix_p_value)
print("Degrees of Freedom:", netflix_dof)

# Print the results for Amazon Prime dataset
print("\nAmazon Prime Chi-square Test Results:")
print("Chi-square Statistic:", amazon_chi2_statistic)
print("p-value:", amazon_p_value)
print("Degrees of Freedom:", amazon_dof)

Netflix Chi-square Test Results:
Chi-square Statistic: 12627.328925952224
p-value: 0.0
Degrees of Freedom: 4342

Amazon Prime Chi-square Test Results:
Chi-square Statistic: 18784.93514962369
p-value: 0.0
Degrees of Freedom: 8300

The Chi-square test results with a p-value of 0.0 for both platforms indicate a strong association between the genres and content ratings.
